Inflation, in Europe, overlaps with food
Accelerated inflation, measured in the euro area, is mainly due to the rapid increase in food prices.
In November, the price increase in the 13 euro area countries was more significant than expected, after an inflation rate of 2.6 per cent in October, an annual inflation of 3.1 per cent was recorded, according to the Statistics Office of the European Community located in Luxembourg.
Official forecasts indicated only 3 percent, Bloomberg said.
Unlike the central banks of the United States, Britain and Canada, the European Central Bank (ECB) has not lowered the leading interest rate by saying that the decline in interest rates, with the rise in commodity prices and the fall in unemployment rate, would lead to a spiral of inflation.
The ECB would like to keep the inflation rate below but close to 2%.
According to one analyst, it is Catch 22 for the ECB: "we need to deter" inflation in order to no longer have to intervene on this issue later.
In Germany, the inflation rate of 3.3 percent is a record in the last twelve years, and in Spain, it has risen from 3.6 to 4.1.
Inflation in the euro area has begun due to the rapid rise in food and energy prices.
Cereal market shares have increased by 88 percent and the soybean market has also reached its highest value since 1973.
The price of food oil and dairy products also increased considerably in 2007.
This year, the world oil price increased by 52 percent and last month, a barrel of black gold cost almost <0x24>100.
According to the ECB, in 2008 the inflation rate will rise from 2.1, this year to 2.5 percent, but in 2009 it will fall to 1.9.
According to analysts, the 12-month inflation rate remains around 3 percent, however, over the next 3 to 4 months, the average annual rate will be 2.1 percent.
At the same time, they expect the ECB to double its steering rate in 2008.
