74 per cent of people would say no to enrolment rights in higher education, 79% would say no to consultation fees, and 84 per cent would say no to hospital stays.
When we look at only the same proportions of people who expressed their intention to vote in the referendum, 81, 84 and 89 per cent of voters would reject the introduction of enrollment fees, consultation fees and hospital stay fees, respectively.
Auchan is the most expensive, Tesco has increased its prices by nearly twenty percent
The hypermarkets located in the commercial triangle of Budaörs have maintained the average price increase of 16 percent over the past year as the VAT rate has not increased this year.
Article of Daily Economy (Daily Economy)
This year, in the commercial triangle of Budaörs, the usual daily Christmas Basket also increased by 16 percent on average, with a value increase significantly higher than a thousand forints appearing in all hypermarkets.
Prices, “already flying” in major grocery stores in December, have no longer risen sharply compared to the previous high base.
However, consumers are obviously shocked to see that items bought well below nine thousand forints last year now cost more than ten thousand forints.
The Daily Basket in the surveyed hypermarkets exceeded at least 91 forints, the psychological threshold of ten thousand forints.
And the highest value of the basket was 10,573 forints.
(In 2003, this value was 6,800 forints.)
Prices for Unicum and live fish have remained almost at last year's level, however, prices for turkey, nuts and pavot have risen sharply.
In stores, the price of flour and bread followed data from the KSH (Central Institute of Statistics) but, at Auchan, bread was found at just 139 forints.
Competition did not lower the price of the product below 200 forints.
It was surprising to see, also in this hypermarket, that the price of the two-liter bottle of Coca-Cola was below 200 forints, so it cost only 257 forints the bottle included.
It only prevents this year, in terms of Daily Basket, Auchan was the most expensive and Cora the cheapest.
According to our calculations, Cora increased the price of its daily basket by 15 percent while Tesco and Auchan increased them by about 18 and 18 percent, respectively.
By comparing last year’s most expensive basket and this year’s cheapest basket, we find a 12 percent difference while the difference between last year’s cheapest and this year’s most expensive basket is 21 percent.
Prices increased by an average of 1,480 forints.
Last year, prices increased by an average of 1,206 forints, while knowing that the impact of the increase in the VAT rate was already noted in last year’s Christmas prices.
This process made trade perplexing, hypermarkets could not visibly determine what margin to apply to products as they were unable to predict the impact of price changes on consumers.
(If a trader miscalculates the rotation of a product, he risk losing a large profit on the margin adapted to the intensity of the trade.)
Due to the change in the VAT rate, the increase in daily basket prices has evolved so excessively that the most expensive basket was 1,720 forints above the 2006 value, while the difference between the cheapest baskets was only 844 forints.
This year, the difference was not so excessive as the value of the most expensive basket was higher by 1,630 forints than last year and the prices of the cheapest also increased by 1,284 forints.
As we approached the two Christmas seasons, we saw a catastrophic increase in prices, in less than 20 months daily consumer goods prices rose by more than 30 percent in hypermarkets.
(This does not necessarily confirm KSH’s data: for some essential foods, the Institute of Statistics found a price increase of more than 30 percent in 12 months.
This is the case, for example, for flour and eggs.)
According to the Daily Basket of the latter, this seems almost absurd since the price level of this product, already quite expensive last year, has increased by just over 10 percent compared to the base.
According to the indices, flour suppliers are in a stronger position than egg suppliers because they have succeeded in accepting the brutal price increases by multinationals as well.
In the commercial gold triangle, hypermarkets do not complain, they are constantly recording good years.
According to our experiences, most customers no longer look at prices in the three hypermarkets visited.
They buy everything in quantity, they take long-term foods by pallets.
On Wednesday morning, major queues formed at the box offices of the three hypermarkets as the number of customers increased dramatically.
Now, according to our information, the turnover is less important in the province, many multinationals complain to survey companies that they do not even reach the expected turnover, not only for food but also for sustainable consumer goods.
Many hospitals are saving on disinfectants
This year, more than a thousand infections, mainly caused by the misuse of antibiotics, have been recorded in hospitals.
The hygienic conditions of hospitals, the insufficient number of beds, the overcrowding of medical staff do not help to block infections, says the chief physician of the National Center for Epidemiology.
Many hospitals are also saving on disinfectants
Not long ago an MRSA infection was diagnosed at János Hospital Traumatology Service.
Antibiotic-resistant bacteria were detected in a man hospitalized after a serious accident.
The patient was isolated.
At the beginning of the year, a similar infection occurred in the same place.
The injured in a serious car accident left the hospital but soon after he had to return due to an MRSA infection and since then the doctors have not been able to perform him an important operation because of the bacteria in his body.
As of 10 December this year, 1,094 hospital infections generated by a multi-resistant pathogen have been reported to the National System of Nosocomial Surveillance, said Karolina Böröcz, the head physician of the National Center for Epidemiology.
Knowing that it is the number of infections caused by a multi-resistant pathogen that has actually been recorded in hospitals and for the rest we have no information.
Approximately two-thirds of the infections (683 infections) were caused by MRSAs, i.e. staphylococcus aureus resistant to methylline-oxacilline.
One third of people carry the bacteria Staphylococcus aureus (SA) in their nose without developing a disease.
SA infections (such as angina, amygdalite, skin infections, traumatic infections) respond well to antibiotics, they are easily curable.
However, if antibiotics are used excessively or inappropriately, the bacteria, which responds well to antibiotics, will develop a good antibiotic-resistant bacteria that will rapidly proliferate in poor hospital conditions.
In case of temporary or prolonged malfunction of the immune system, this bacterium can cause serious hospital infections, such as traumatic infection or septicemia, in elderly patients, with low weight or with a weakened body.
According to the director of the hospital János, there is nothing special in MRSA infections, these infections are part of the daily life of hospitals.
Above all, we should not confuse the infection with the epidemic, we don’t find MRSA only or we don’t look for them, Tibor Nyulasi said.
SAs are resistant to antibiotics.
"These patients are isolated, the care staff put on rubber gloves and protective masks and we have antibiotics suitable for treating them," said Tibor Nyulasi.
A priori, hospitalized patients are examined if they are carriers of MRSA, but infection can not always be prevented.
Sample sampling is not fashionable.
The vast majority of infections caused by MRSA could be prevented, but current conditions and circumstances are not favorable in Hungarian hospitals to prevent the development and proliferation of multi-resistance pathogens, says Karolina Börocz.
As this infection occurs mainly in hospitals and residences for the elderly, hospitals should monitor hospitalized patients and immediately isolate patients with MRSA.
However, microbiological sampling is not fashionable in Hungarian hospitals.
It should be noted that the National Social Security Fund does not finance these examinations.
Most cases only see the day if MRSA infection is detectable on the patient, the chief doctor of the epidemiological center said.
The European Union has strict recommendations on the appropriate use of antibiotics in human medicine and there are also Hungarian guidelines for the cure of certain infections and syndromes.
Efforts must be made to target antibiotic therapy, in other words microbiological examinations should be carried out to prevent drug resistance, but hospitals do not always take this into account.
Microbiological sampling is even more rare in outpatient care and basic care, Karolina Börocz said.
Many hospitals are saving on disinfectants
Scientific evidence shows that MRSAs proliferate from one patient to another most often through medical personnel.
It is therefore essential to wash your hands, to wear gloves and protective masks, but significant gaps are detected in hospitals also in this area.
MRSAs proliferate by infection transmitted by inhalation of droplets and by contact. However, due to conditions in Hungarian hospitals, the infected patient can not always be isolated.
In addition, the rooms are often full, the beds are often too close to each other while in the end of the epidemic, patients should be at least 1.5 meters away from each other.
Unfortunately, we also find that hospitals, in a difficult financial situation, are saving on disinfectants, they lack nurses, there are many patients, so the risk of contamination is even greater, Karolina Börocz said.
According to Karolina Böröcz, in hospitals or preventive measures are observed, the number of infections is demonstrably lower or then the proliferation of the pathogen can be blocked.
Government Project Against MRSA
Treatment of MRSA infection represents exorbitant expenses for social security boxes, which is why this infection is being fought everywhere.
In England, for example, the government has established a program to prevent or reduce the incidence of MRSA.
According to the published data, this program is effective and MRSA infections show a decreasing trend in England.
The European Centre for Disease Prevention and Control (ECDC) highlights among its priorities the prevention of the incidence of multiresistant pathogens (such as MRSAs as well) as the prevention of hospital infections caused by these pathogens.
