The British Army recruits on YouTube
The units of the British Army communicate, on the video sharing site, recordings made during its operations in Iraq and Afghanistan with the aim of becoming popular.
First, it is the British Air Force (RAF) that has become passionate about YouTube: special units operating in Afghanistan are loading video sequences on operations against the Taliban since March 2006, the BBC announced.
These recordings, taken with the help of miniature cameras mounted on the helmet, are monitored at the air force operations headquarters in Kandahar and then transferred to London or the countrymen charge them over the Internet.
The political message is unavoidable
Air Force troops have already passed 139 sequences on the net through this path and their "chain" has been watched by more than 75,000 people.
The British Ministry of Defence registered as "defenceheadquarters" in the spring of 2007 and it communicates videos on operations in Iraq and Afghanistan while the Ministry of Commonwealth (Commonwealth Office) and the international peacekeeping forces also have their own MFIs in Iraq.
Mission in Afghanistan.
According to the initial objective of the air force, the videos were posted on the net for recruitment, and according to the Ministry of Defence, they were also used to make the public aware of the real objectives of the army's presence abroad.
The propaganda published in this way costs virtually nothing compared to the usual recruitment advertisements made on television, Gordon Mackenzie, a defense consultant, told the BBC. On the other hand, it also inevitably carries a political message, as it specifically justifies the well-founded government by media operations.
The Americans played a game
The army is concerned because, apart from the carefully composed and censored videos, amateur videos are passed on the sharing site which also present, for example, the death of soldiers: in "official" propaganda films, a bit hypocritical, officers do not avoid talking about the present losses, but they never cling to the blood.
In addition, many videos had already been posted on the net showing the areas of operations in Iraq and Afghanistan that were being carried out on a real mission, but the British army has only recently been packing for loading these videos.
Americans do the recruitment a bit differently using the free downloadable shooting game America's Army. In this game the player can place himself directly in the place of the soldiers as part of a more or less real simulation.
