The integration of Slovak pupils into British schools is bad
The number of children originating in Eastern European countries in British schools is increasing, causing the remainder to be concerned about the development of local education.
The integration of the Eastern Europeans is currently facing a series of obstacles.
British schools even see cases where conflicts between immigrants and descendants of indigenous peoples turn into violence.
The case of North Kent, where the remaining conflicts of opposition and immigrants of Slovak origin are beginning to intensify, illustrates well the problem of the integration of children from Eastern Europe.
Disputes, gossip and gossip between students have transposed into parental relationships.
The situation went so far that police arrested a Slovak woman in Chatham who hit a 10-year-old student with an iron bar.
The accused defended himself by claiming that the boy had insulted him with racist words.
Police were also forced to intervene following the attack on a Slovak immigrant led by two teenagers.
The young girls allegedly made racist remarks to the man and threw stones at him.
“When we got home, a young man climbed up the bus stop and started scratching on us.
