Cuba, the most beautiful island in the Caribbean
For visitors, it is truly an island of freedom.
Everything you expect from your vacation can be achieved if you make the right choice.
Golden and white beaches like snow, high waves or then a calm sea like a pond.
Palms and all-inclusive with servers offering you on the beach a pizza, ice cream or drinkable cocktails.
Kitesurfing, golf and roulette.
On the islands of the Caribbean Sea, you will find this list not only in its entirety, but enriched.
But there is only one island on which you will find much more and it is Cuba, the largest and most beautiful island in the Greater Antilles.
At the time of the Spanish, Cuba had been the base of their invasion of America.
Christopher Columbus called it the most beautiful place the human eye has ever seen.
Havana became the deposit and transshipment site of the treasures that the Spaniards had stolen and carried to Europe.
Then came the American era.
The Hotel Nacional was built in the early 1920s.
It was Lucky Luciano, one of the leaders of the American mafia, who built it, since everything that was a crime in the U.S. (especially under the ban) was admitted and supported in Cuba: drugs, gambling, prostitution.
Among his clients were, among other things,
Winston Churchill, Ava Gardner, Frank Sinatra.
In Havana, high-rise buildings grew and cars, belonging to the cult symbols of the 1950s, circulated on the broad boulevards.
Ernest Hemingway bought a property in San Francisco de Paula, near Havana, and, in Cojímar, he had his yacht.
Stars of the show business and politicians from across America left their signatures on the walls of the Bodeguita del Medio.
What about today?
You can leave your autograph on the walls of the Bodeguita of Havana.
In the bar of the Hotel Nacional, a luxury hotel, you will be able to mix the cocktail of your choice.
And these cult cars still circulate in Havana, as the once imported jigoli and fiat have long since been rotten, in such a salty and wet climate.
Although Havana, especially the oldest part, is substantially decrepit, nowhere else in the vicinity there are as many splendid colonial monuments as there are precisely there.
Other places become more beautiful, for example Trinidad.
Since tourism brings the money if necessary, its development has the green light.
Over the past fifteen years, new hotels have grown not only in Havana, but especially in Varader, on the coast of the province of Holguín, and also on small islands such as Cayo Coco, Cayo Guillermo and others.
Cuba still offers a fantasy that is unique in the world and will be appreciated especially by fans of small trains.
The cane had come home from the plantations spread in the candies on a narrow track by small steam and motor trains.
Their rolling stock has not been renewed for decades and this is how you can see small locomotives running there whose contemporaries are only elsewhere in museums.
Where to take his steps?
The majority of visitors do not miss the most well-known places.
There is no need to write long about Varadero or Havana.
Otherwise, remember that in the property of Hemingway, already mentioned, there is a museum and that anyone who loves this writer should not miss the visit.
The valley of Vinjales in the west of the island is one of the most picturesque corners of Cuba.
An exuberant vegetation grows on a limestone soil.
Mogotes, limestone balloons and rocks rise in candles from the bottom of the valley, and since fertile land has taken hold in their bowels, even its rotten rocks are covered with a very dense vegetative carpet.
The valley is the place where Cuban tobacco of the best quality is probably grown.
You can find the final form of this product if you visit one of Havana’s cigar factories.
Someone may also find it interesting that this is where Major Zeman’s Chilean episode was filmed.
Trinidad
The ancient city was founded shortly after the Spanish colonized the island.
It is the market that the slave trade and the sugar trade that brought it glory and wealth.
Wealth has been embodied in the beauty and vicinity of this small town.
Colonial Spanish architecture, significantly influenced by later French settlers, has barely changed in four centuries.
Trinidad, located between the sea and the Escambray mountainous massif, is a place so far apart that even in the 1950s, there was no road connecting this region with the rest of the country.
This isolation allowed him to stay away.
Nothing was built, and that’s why nothing was demolished, everyone just had a roof over their head.
If you have more time in Trinidad than an afternoon, then it is worth going to see also interesting places in the surroundings, such as Playa Ancón Beach or the Sugar Valley.
Then, in the evening, it is customary to go to the Casa de la Música which animates after sunset and where the music is only softened in the early morning.
Baracoa
Some refer to this borough located in the far east of Cuba as the most beautiful on the island.
This opinion is certainly already influenced by the path that leads to it.
The two roads leading there from Guantánamo must cross high and steep mountains and cross a landscape almost without signs of human activity.
UNESCO has listed the East of Cuba, thanks to its intact landscape, on the World Heritage List.
It produces the best chocolate, at the church, there is the cross of Christopher Columbus (in fact, it was born about a hundred years after Columbus's passing) and from the hill where the old fortress and the current hotel El Castillo, you can see several mountains table, of which El Yucque is the most famous.
About coffee, rum, cigarettes, mountain massif Sierra Maestra, Troyes Bay and the island of Pinos, Tropicana cabaret, the sanctuary of the patron saint of Cuba Caridad del Cobre, Santeria, African religions practiced by their descendants.
Only, as we say, it is better to see it once.
In Afghanistan, allies are passive, Americans say
The lack of troops and necessary equipment, according to the United States, influences the operation of the mission in Afghanistan.
According to Defense Minister Robert Gates, NATO should outline a concrete plan for the years to come.
The mission in Afghanistan is not taking place as it should, the representatives of the countries that have troops in the southern part of the country agreed in Edinburgh, Scotland.
In addition to the growing opposition on the part of the Taliban, the eight States involved are also discussing plans for the future and the coordination of the Allies.
While the U.S. called for greater activity this week through Secretary of Defense Robert Gates, the United Kingdom prioritizes the strengthening of the Afghan government's authority and the intensification of development assistance.
“The development in Afghanistan is perceptible, but military power can only be part of the solution.
The other is to allow the residents to start a new development of the economy and security themselves," British Defense Minister Des Browne told the BBC.
Eighty-nine percent
Afghan insurgents’ activity is, according to U.S. military data, the most intense in the last five years.
The number of violent actions increased by 27 per cent compared to last year, up to 60 per cent in Helmand province in the south of the country.
NATO countries have about 40,000 troops in Afghanistan, almost a quarter of them in the south.
But according to the United States, the Allies have reached their absolute limit both in the organization and equipment of the troops.
Concretely, they are asking for other helicopters, soldiers and experts to train Afghan troops.
“We will have to seriously think about the concrete goals for the coming period, as well as how to achieve them,” Gates said.
NATO Secretary-General Jaap de Hoop made similar speeches today.
“I’m not happy with what we have on land and in the air in Afghanistan.
We have about eighty percent of the soldiers and equipment we would need, and that’s not enough,” De Hoop told Reuters at the end of talks with the Japanese government in Tokyo, which lasted three days.
Who is passive
In recent months there have also been conflicts between the countries involved on the question of whether all the allies are actually doing their best in Afghanistan.
For example, Germany has been criticized for its passivity.
"The Germans have a relatively large representation in Afghanistan.
But they are committed to areas where violence is minimal, so the fighting requirements they are subject to are not as stringent as those in the South and East parts of the country where we operate,” Gates said.
This week, the British tabloid Sun described the German soldiers as cowardly.
"The Afghan scoundrels discovered: the Germans play, while ours fight," Sun wrote in a document supplemented with photos of German soldiers playing table tennis.
The German newspaper Bild went into counterattack by publishing a photo of a British squad during a rugby match in southern Afghanistan.
