However, at the beginning of September, thanks to better-than-expected changes in the state budget, the ministry reduced the expected sum to 152.8 billion crowns.
The sum is essentially made up of the state budget deficit, which is apparently going to reach 76 billion kroner this year, instead of the 91.3 billion kroner originally planned.
Secondly, these are the maximum sources for the Czech Consolidation Agency, namely 13.3 billion kroner, the reserve of 10 billion kroner for the payment of pensions, the financing of state pension securities for 43 billion kroner and the repayment of European bonds of 1 billion kroner.
She appeared today before a court in Khartoum for appointing a pelted bear
The British teacher judged in Sudan for insulting Islam was sentenced Thursday evening by a Khartoum court to 15 days in prison and expulsion, her lawyer said.
The British woman was accused of letting students aged 6-7 give the name of Muhammad to a pelted bear while any representation of the Prophet of Islam is illegal.
She was subject to a penalty of whistleblowers.
The 54-year-old British teacher in office at the Unity High School in Khartoum, Sudan, was arrested at her home on Sunday and charged with violation of Islam and sedition, under article 125 of the Sudanese Penal Code, following complaints by parents of minor offenders.
The story actually goes back to September, when this teacher asks her students, aged 6/7, to choose a name for the class pellets bear.
“Eight names come out of the mouths of the children, including Hassan, Abdullah and Mohammed,” said Robert Boulos, the school’s director.
Finally, after a vote in the class, 20 children out of 23 chose Mohamed as their preferred surname.
Muhammad is of course the name of the Muslim prophet, but above all a very common name in Sudan.
The children then made a book for the class with the photo of the bear followed by the legend "My name is Mohamed".
The bear itself did not bear any labels with this name, but the problem is simply that of the representation of the prophet considered an insult to Islam.
One of Gillian Gibbons’ Muslim colleagues, a teacher at the same school in Sudan, said he knew her well and that she would never have done anything that could be offensive to a religious faith, “I just regret that she asked the children to “vote” her name.
Opinion shared by many students of the instructor who describe her as “very attentive to her students” and “who never talks about religion in class”.
Remember that the surname Mohamed is also the second most given surname in Britain, it is written in English in 14 different ways.
This name often chosen by Muslim families is a way to honor the Prophet (often given to the first child of a family).
But what are the rules regarding the use of this name?
Can you give it to a toy?
This is, of course, a question of interpretation.
They failed on Wednesday to reach an agreement on the future status of the province at the last negotiating session in Vienna.
In the end, failure.
The Serbians and Albanians of Kosovo completed a sixth and final meeting in Baden, Austria, on Wednesday morning, without being able to overcome their divergences over the future status of the separatist province.
“It is regrettable that the parties were not able to reach an agreement on the status,” European Ombudsman Wolfgang Ischinger said at a press conference in Vienna.
Emphasizing that peace in the region was “at stake”, his American counterpart, Frank Wisner, urged Belgrade and Pristina to respect their commitments to preserve peace and dialogue beyond the end of the negotiations.
“We don’t expect violence immediately, but we’re entering a very difficult time,” he said, adding that “obvious tensions exist.”
End of Mediation on 10 December
The mediators of the Troika, which brings together the European Union, the United States and Russia, will visit Serbia and Kosovo for the last time on Monday.
The future of the 90 percent-populated province could become clearer when Ischinger, Wisner and Russian mediator Alexander Botsane-Khartchenko submit their report to the UN Security Council by December 10.
The discussions in Baden, near Vienna, constituted the sixth and last session of negotiations since the Troika was charged with a new mediation by the United Nations last August.
Americans and Europeans believe that their mediation will end on December 10.
The Russians, who have already blocked the granting of independence to the Security Council in Kosovo, insist on continuing negotiations beyond this deadline.
“Russia was and remains committed to a negotiated solution, a compromise solution,” said Botsane-Khartchenko.
Declaration of Unilateral Independence?
After eight years of Kosovo's administration, Westerners believe that EU-supervised independence is the only viable solution.
Pristina says she is ready to proclaim it unilaterally if the Security Council does not act in its favour.
Belgrade insists on increased autonomy.
"Unfortunately, no agreement has been found," Kosovo Autonomous Authority President Fatmir Sejdiu said at the hotel in Baden, where these "last chance negotiations" had been held since Monday.
Hashim Thaci, a former commander of the Kosovo rebellion and future Prime Minister of the province, has expressed his regrets.
But he added that the autonomy plan presented by Belgrade “belonged to a past that led to murders and deportations.”
"Domino Effect"
Serbian President Boris Tadic considered that a compromise was still envisaged, warning the Albanian majority of Kosovo against the consequences of a unilateral declaration of the province's independence.
Belgrade said in particular to fear a “domino effect” in a region still weakened by the 1990s wars of independence.
“For Serbia, it does not mean that a compromise is impossible.”
On Tuesday, the Serbian delegation had insisted that any decision be returned exclusively to the Security Council, where its Russian ally has a veto right.
"The Parliament of Kosovo will have the last word"
“Only a solution within the Security Council is acceptable for Serbia,” Serbian Prime Minister Vojislav Kostunica said.
“These negotiations lasted two years.
They must end as they began: in the Security Council.”
To journalists, Fatmir Sedjiu had responded that "the parliament of Kosovo will have the last word on the status", adding that any unilateral declaration of independence by Albanians would be made "in consultation" with the Westerners.
Bush breaks deal between Israelis and Palestinians
President George W. Bush announced at the opening of the international peace conference, which he held on Tuesday in Annapolis, Maryland, that Israelis and Palestinians had finally agreed on a joint statement.
He said Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Olmert and Palestinian President Mahmoud Abbas had agreed to immediately engage in negotiations to find a definitive settlement of the disputed 60-year-old between their two peoples.
In the presence of the two men, Bush promised that he would do anything to help them conclude a “peace treaty” by the end of 2008.
