A Heavy Memory
After more than 60 years of confidentiality, the Nazi archives of Bad Arolsen, which trace the fate of the 17.5 million victims of the Hitler regime, are freely accessible.
The 47 million archives, stored over 27 km of line in Bad Arolsen (Hesse), were so far only accessible for “humanitarian” purposes, i.e. individually and nominally, at the request of an ex-victim or its right-holders.
The eleven states in charge of their management – including Germany, France, Israel and the United States – agreed in May 2006 to open them to researchers and historians.
The process of ratification of this agreement by all States has been completed, and the opening has been effective since yesterday.
Sensitive information
The access of historians to Bad Arolsen will allow research to be carried out “particularly on the displacement of prisoners, the population of the camps and the health of forced workers,” says Reto Meistern, the director of these archives managed by the International Committee of the Red Cross (ICRC).
Until recently, several States, including Germany, had objected to the openness of these nominative documents to the public, due to the sensitive nature of certain information.
Such as supposed homosexuality or mental disability of some victims of deportation.
The records of the concentration camps or arrest warrants established by the Gestapo had been assembled after the war for a practical purpose: to find the civilians deported or subjected to compulsory labour and, if necessary, to provide them with proof of their detention, in order to open the way for their compensation.
Even today in Bad Arolsen, more than 300 permanent employees handle tens of thousands of individual applications.
However, for a part of the scientific community, access to Bad Arolsen is of limited interest.
“There is nothing fundamentally new to expect from these documents,” said Professor Wolfgang Benz, director of the Centre for Research on Anti-Semitism at the Technische Universität Berlin in 2006.
