Venus is the Earth's hell twin.
Despite its hostile atmosphere to life, Venus looks more like Earth than previously thought: the European space probe "Venus Express" has discovered lightning in the atmosphere and wind turbulence at the poles, similar to those that appear on Earth in winter.
For nearly three decades, scientists have assumed that there are flashes on Venus.
The European probe "Venus Express" today brought evidence - it detected electromagnetic waves at the limit of the atmosphere: lightning flashes on Venus explode at an altitude of about 56 kilometres of cloud cloud, reports Christopher Russel of the University of California in "The Magazin in Los Angeles".
According to the famous theory of cyprin, lightning would have made life on Earth appear: the storm would have stimulated reactions in the oceans that led to the formation of amino acids, the cornerstone of life.
This is not the case on Venus: “If there was life, it must have been at a very ancient date in history,” explains Sean Solomon of the Carnegie Institution in Washington.
There should be little living things on the surface of Venus today: the atmosphere is about a hundred times denser than on Earth, sometimes with temperatures of 500 degrees.
“Venus may be the hellish twin on Earth, but it remains a twin,” Russell said.
Why Venus, which looks so much like Earth in mass and dimensions, has been struck by such a different evolution, is the fundamental question of the ASE mission.
The departure of Venus Express in November 2005 was an important step in Venus research, as no more probes were on the way to exploring the planet since the 1980s.
According to the researchers, the latest research results that have now been presented in several "Nature" articles not only highlight the uniqueness of Venus within the solar system.
They also show that the points in common with the Earth of our neighboring planet are more numerous than were supposed at first.
Thus, in addition to the wind turbulence already known at the north pole, the researchers found a cloud turbulence at the south pole, which rotates even faster.
The phenomenon is reminiscent of air currents in the Earth's hemispheres in winter, wrote a team of researchers around Giuseppe Piccioni of the Italian Institute of Astrophysics Spatiale and Cosmic Physics.
The second planet in the solar system has almost the same mass as Earth and is, with a diameter of 12.100 kilometers, almost as large.
The planet classified as a night or morning star orbits the sun in just 225 days.
However, it turns on itself much more slowly: a Venetian day lasts 243 days.
Although Venus, with surface temperatures of 460 degrees Celsius and a pressure of 92 bar, barely recalls Earth, scientists assume that the two planets formed under similar conditions.
On both, the water accumulated and remained on Earth in the form of oceans, but was lost in space on Venus.
And while carbon dioxide has fixed itself on Earth in the form of carbonate, it constitutes most of the atmosphere on Venus.
